    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "01192b45_48c17dd6",
        "filename": "compat/android/elf.h",
        "patchSetId": 10
      },
      "lineNbr": 50,
      "author": {
        "id": 1172779
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-01T20:14:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It\u0027s defined in linux/elf.h, but including both linux/elf.h and elf.h directly results in name collisions.\n\nhttps://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/crashpad/crashpad/+/455659",
      "parentUuid": "1084149e_476df181",
      "revId": "83c3acca564849bab1705b4b2d39c9c6f53baeb9",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "2914a65b_91552cd4",
        "filename": "compat/android/elf.h",
        "patchSetId": 10
      },
      "lineNbr": 50,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-01T21:09:22Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e It\u0027s defined in linux/elf.h, but including both linux/elf.h and elf.h directly results in name collisions.\n\nThe bit in the comment that said “normally provided by \u003clinux/elf.h\u003e, included by \u003celf.h\u003e” must be what led me astray. I suggest rewording to make the point more clearly, which I now understand is based on:\n\n • These types and the macro are normally provided by \u003clinux/elf.h\u003e\n • In unified headers, \u003celf.h\u003e includes \u003clinux/elf.h\u003e\n • In traditional headers, \u003celf.h\u003e doesn’t, and furthermore, the two headers can’t both be included in the same translation unit due to collisions.",
      "parentUuid": "01192b45_48c17dd6",
      "revId": "83c3acca564849bab1705b4b2d39c9c6f53baeb9",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "3aeeacdf_02b19146",
        "filename": "snapshot/elf/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 10
      },
      "lineNbr": 213,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-01T03:22:28Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This is current_address_, it just happens to be inside a segment, right?",
      "revId": "83c3acca564849bab1705b4b2d39c9c6f53baeb9",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "e8cdd882_f0caa581",
        "filename": "snapshot/elf/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 10
      },
      "lineNbr": 249,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-01T03:22:28Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "or 8-byte for ELF64?",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 249,
        "startChar": 26,
        "endLine": 249,
        "endChar": 32
      },
      "revId": "83c3acca564849bab1705b4b2d39c9c6f53baeb9",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa84619e_94db604a",
        "filename": "snapshot/elf/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 10
      },
      "lineNbr": 249,
      "author": {
        "id": 1172779
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-01T20:14:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Nope.\nThis source says 64-bit objects should have 8-byte alignment, 32-bit, 4-byte alignment:\nhttp://www.sco.com/developers/gabi/latest/ch5.pheader.html\n\nThis source says both 64-bit and 32-bit objects have 4-byte alignment:\nhttps://docs.oracle.com/cd/E23824_01/html/819-0690/chapter6-18048.html\n\nObservation so far (and the kernel header\u0027s definition for Elf64_Nhdr) says 64-bit objects use 4-byte aligned notes.",
      "parentUuid": "e8cdd882_f0caa581",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 249,
        "startChar": 26,
        "endLine": 249,
        "endChar": 32
      },
      "revId": "83c3acca564849bab1705b4b2d39c9c6f53baeb9",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "e46e3ab6_7335430d",
        "filename": "snapshot/elf/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 10
      },
      "lineNbr": 249,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-01T21:09:22Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e Nope.\n\u003e This source says 64-bit objects should have 8-byte alignment, 32-bit, 4-byte alignment:\n\u003e http://www.sco.com/developers/gabi/latest/ch5.pheader.html\n\u003e \n\u003e This source says both 64-bit and 32-bit objects have 4-byte alignment:\n\u003e https://docs.oracle.com/cd/E23824_01/html/819-0690/chapter6-18048.html\n\u003e \n\u003e Observation so far (and the kernel header\u0027s definition for Elf64_Nhdr) says 64-bit objects use 4-byte aligned notes.\n\nI asked because line 238 sets align to 8 with NhdrType \u003d Elf64_Nhdr. Is that wrong?",
      "parentUuid": "fa84619e_94db604a",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 249,
        "startChar": 26,
        "endLine": 249,
        "endChar": 32
      },
      "revId": "83c3acca564849bab1705b4b2d39c9c6f53baeb9",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "a9161558_3e3c31a2",
        "filename": "snapshot/elf/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 10
      },
      "lineNbr": 249,
      "author": {
        "id": 1172779
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-01T21:31:24Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "For Linux, Elf64_Nhdr and Elf32_Nhdr are equivalent. Both use 32-bit types.\nI check anyways, in case some other OS (Fuchsia) does use 64-bit types.\nI\u0027ll update the comment to specify Linux, specifically, uses 4-byte alignment.",
      "parentUuid": "e46e3ab6_7335430d",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 249,
        "startChar": 26,
        "endLine": 249,
        "endChar": 32
      },
      "revId": "83c3acca564849bab1705b4b2d39c9c6f53baeb9",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "a9353176_b31fc86d",
        "filename": "snapshot/elf/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 10
      },
      "lineNbr": 250,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-01T03:22:28Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This comment is terrifying. Is this really what other readers do?",
      "revId": "83c3acca564849bab1705b4b2d39c9c6f53baeb9",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "cdc5d707_3560a5ec",
        "filename": "snapshot/elf/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 10
      },
      "lineNbr": 250,
      "author": {
        "id": 1172779
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-01T20:14:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It doesn\u0027t look like readelf or GDB do any special handling when reading from note segments. They assume all the notes are 4-byte aligned so I suspect they would fail if they tried to read sequential notes where the first note is mis-aligned. Normally, they read notes using the section header table, which gives the start address of each note individually. They only fall back to the program header table for core files, but I think .note.android.ident wouldn\u0027t normally end up there.",
      "parentUuid": "a9353176_b31fc86d",
      "revId": "83c3acca564849bab1705b4b2d39c9c6f53baeb9",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "b0ea6ba6_6ec1f1d7",
        "filename": "snapshot/elf/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 10
      },
      "lineNbr": 250,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-01T21:09:22Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e It doesn\u0027t look like readelf or GDB do any special handling when reading from note segments. They assume all the notes are 4-byte aligned so I suspect they would fail if they tried to read sequential notes where the first note is mis-aligned. Normally, they read notes using the section header table, which gives the start address of each note individually. They only fall back to the program header table for core files, but I think .note.android.ident wouldn\u0027t normally end up there.\n\nRather than inferring the alignment, can we use ElfN_Phdr::p_align?",
      "parentUuid": "cdc5d707_3560a5ec",
      "revId": "83c3acca564849bab1705b4b2d39c9c6f53baeb9",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
